			<wp:comment_date_gmt><![CDATA[2018-02-28 01:58:20]]></wp:comment_date_gmt>
			<wp:comment_content><![CDATA[It's still difficult, but I use Trello quite a lot to plan out what I want to learn. Using a sprint methodology is also really helpful (assuming that you keep up with them) - that is, take a time period, one week or two weeks, and make a tiny goal. For example, if you've found a course you're interested in, then break that course up into parts and complete it in weeklong sprints (how much can you complete this week?). Similarly, I've done the same sort of thing with audio books, tutorials, and other learning materials outside of courses. I think making tiny plans is key.

The other thing is being okay with not learning ALL THE THINGS. I hang my hat on development, so that's where I focus my learning efforts. I don't jump on trying to learn more about new video tools or new platforms for this and that. I focus on trying to be a better developer. It's the tradeoff of breadth vs depth. Once you've figured out what you love about this work, once you've tried a bunch of different things, then you can figure out where you want to go deep and be okay with letting the other stuff go.]]></wp:comment_content>
